(1023, 2, '2014-06-09 18:39:48', '2014-06-09 18:39:48', '<h2><span style=\"color: #7d3a46;\"><strong>THANK YOU TO VERNON AND DISTRICT WOMEN\'S CENTRE</strong>:</span></h2>\r\nIt was a bittersweet moment.\r\n\r\nWe were gifted with a significant donation for the women and children we serve but it came at the cost of a local agency.\r\n\r\nThe Vernon and District Women\'s Centre closed its doors in May 2011.\r\n\r\nThe board has remained active and hopeful that the political climate would change and funding to continue their work with vulnerable women in our community could continue.\r\n\r\nThis, unfortunately, has not been the case.\r\n\r\nThe board of the Women\'s Centre is preparing to dissolve and in doing so has generously gifted their remaining funds to continue to assist women and children.\r\n\r\nWe extend a heartfelt thank you to the board for this meaningful gift with we plan to put towards running groups for women who have experienced violence, mental ill health and substance use issues and to continue our work to prevent violence against women and children in our community.\r\n\r\nAgain, <em>Thank you.</em>\r\n\r\nBrooke McLardy, Programs Director and Ninke Beeksma, Executive Director - Vernon Women\'s Transition House Society', 'THANK YOU', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '876-revision-4', '', '', '2014-06-09 18:39:48', '2014-06-09 18:39:48', '', 876, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2014/06/876-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1243, 2, '2015-03-02 18:04:43', '2015-03-02 18:04:43', '<em>Morning Star Staff - Sunday, March 1, 2015</em>\r\n\r\nVernon residents are being urged to honour those special women in their lives. \r\n\r\nAn International Women\'s Day celebration in support of Vernon Women\'s Transition House Society will be held March 8th at the Schubert Centre from 2 to 4 p.m.  \"This event will bring together the community to commemorate the amazing women in all of our lives,\" siad Rosalie Paquette, the Society\'s Awareness and Special Events Coordinator.\r\n\r\nThis celebration is for all ages, women and men alike, and will feature an amazing group of guests speakers as well as live music from women in our very own community.  Refreshments will be provided, as well as some amazing door prizes.\"\r\n\r\nAll proceeds from entry donations (suggested $5 minimum) will go directly to transition house.\r\n\r\nthe Society provides safety and shelter for women and children fleeing abuse.  It also offers women\'s outreach and counselling. \r\n\r\nThis year, take some time to come together for international Women\'s Day and celebrate your mother, sister, wife, and friends,\" said Paquette.', 'WOMEN\'S DAY HELPS TRANSITION HOUSE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1239-revision-3', '', '', '2015-03-02 18:04:43', '2015-03-02 18:04:43', '', 1239, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2015/03/1239-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1025, 2, '2014-06-09 18:40:19', '2014-06-09 18:40:19', '<a href=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/EquineTherapydonation-20132.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-822 aligncenter\" title=\"EquineTherapydonation 2013\" src=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/EquineTherapydonation-20132-300x246.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"417\" height=\"343\" /></a>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Wendy Elrick (left, of Vernon Women\'s Transition House, and Susy Bairstow, of the B.C. Interior Horse Rescue Society, receive $3,700 cash each from Sheila Sperling and Ruby Edwards, with the Horsey Ladies.</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em>Morning Star Staff</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">They came from all over the Interior to socialize, shop and to give back to charity.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">And once again, the annual Okanagan Horsey Ladies Charity Auction proved it has what it takes to give back to the community.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The 16th annual event, at the Spallumcheen Golf and Country Club, brought together 130 women who nominated a total of 12 charities to support that evening.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The top two vote-getters were the B.C. Interior Horse Rescue Society and <strong>Vernon Women\'s Transition House\'s Equine Assisted Therapy Program</strong>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em>\"We are pleased to announce, thanks to the generosity of our sponsors and the ladies bidding, we raised $7,400 (exceeding last year\'s $6,400),\"</em> said Nancy Roman, spokesperson for the Horsey Ladies committee.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em>\"The amount was divided equally and $3,700 was given to each winning charity.\"</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The group has raised a total of $57,000 since beginning its annual fundraisers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em>\"The Horsey Ladies is neither a club nor a society, we have no president of bank account,\"</em> said Roman.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><em>\"We are just a bunch of gals that get together and meet at Christmas and seek out donations throughout the year.  We appreciate and tank all of the local and out-of-town sponsors.\"</em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Besides Roman, the other members of the Horsey Ladies are Ruby Edwards, Elspeth Manning, Michele Gould, Amy Vaughan, Sheila Sperling, Patti Thomas and Ursula McHugh.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"> </p>\r\n&nbsp;', 'EQUINE THERAPY RECEIVES DONATION', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '818-revision-5', '', '', '2014-06-09 18:40:19', '2014-06-09 18:40:19', '', 818, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2014/06/818-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1026, 2, '2014-06-09 18:40:45', '2014-06-09 18:40:45', '<a href=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/DonationOct20131.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone  wp-image-794\" title=\"DonationOct2013\" src=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/DonationOct20131-300x127.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"480\" height=\"233\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<em>Picture and article by Lisa Vandervelde/Morning Star</em>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Members of the New Car Dealers Association of Vernon, Darryl Payeur, of Bannister GM, (third from left) Ross Blankley, of Watkin Motors, Pat Loehndorf, of Bannister Honda, Marty Steele, of Vernon Toyota, Adrian Wyant, of Vernon Hyundai, and Brian Westwell, of Vernon Nissan, present $6,860 to Ninke Beeksma and Marilyn Nakucyj, of Vernon Women\'s Transition House Society.  The money was raised at the New Car Dealers Association of Vernon\'s charity golf tournament.</p>', 'SHOWING SUPPORT', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '792-revision-6', '', '', '2014-06-09 18:40:45', '2014-06-09 18:40:45', '', 792, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2014/06/792-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1027, 2, '2014-06-09 18:40:32', '2014-06-09 18:40:32', 'Click on link below to read an article about our Child &amp; Youth Worker.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Starting-a-conversation-on-healthy-relationships.pdf\">Starting a conversation on healthy relationships</a>', 'STARTING A CONVERSATION ON HEALTHY RELATIONSHIPS', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '806-revision-4', '', '', '2014-06-09 18:40:32', '2014-06-09 18:40:32', '', 806, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2014/06/806-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1028, 2, '2014-06-09 18:41:05', '2014-06-09 18:41:05', '<strong>THANK YOU TO OKANAGAN RESTORATION</strong>\r\n\r\nWe would like to thank <em>Okanagan Restoration</em> - <em>Shane and Andy</em>, for their generous donation of time to paint the interior of our Residence.  As a shelter for 25 women and children seeking shelter from domestic abuse it is important that our Transition House is a warm and welcoming place.  We were also impressed by the professionalism and pride that Shane and Andy took in their work.  Having the kitchen painted has made a world of difference to the main floor.\r\n\r\nThis donation has greatly improved the look and feel of our Transition House and we greatly appreciate it.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #8d3e54;\"><em><strong>Thank you from the Staff and Residents</strong></em></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #8d3e54;\"><em><strong>of </strong></em></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #8d3e54;\"><em><strong>Vernon Women\'s Transition House.</strong></em></span></p>', 'Interior Repainted at Transition House', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '789-revision-4', '', '', '2014-06-09 18:41:05', '2014-06-09 18:41:05', '', 789, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2014/06/789-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1029, 2, '2014-06-09 18:41:20', '2014-06-09 18:41:20', '<a href=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/RenoSign.jpg\"><img class=\"wp-image-770 alignleft\" title=\"RenoSign\" src=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/RenoSign-300x296.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"168\" height=\"160\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe Vernon Women\'s Transition House Society is presently raising funds towards renovating our 11 bedrooms for clients.  Our Transition House is 20 years old and is needing some TLC.  Funds received from our ongoing fundraising campaign will be used for paint, flooring and baseboards, new bed frames and storage drawers, mattresses, bedding and decor for the walls.  As a shelter for some of our most vulnerable community members, we would like to create a warm and welcoming space for the women and children who reside with us.\r\n\r\nWe are looking to our generous community to assist us with accomplishing our renovation project.  In the event a community member or business is willing to donate funds to completely renovate one of our bedrooms, a charitable tax receipt for the amount donated will be provided and the donor will be recognized with a plaque located in the bedroom they have generously assisted to renovate.  All donations of funds, materials or manpower are greatly appreciated.\r\n\r\nIn the event that you would like to assist us with this project, please contact <strong>Brooke McLardy, Programs Director</strong> at <strong>250.542.1122</strong> or at <a href=\"mailto:brooke.mclardy@vwts.ca\">brooke.mclardy@vwts.ca</a>.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Our sincere<em><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong> thank you</strong> </span></em>to the following community organizations who have so graciously donated to our renovation fund</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Nixon Wenger</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Rotary Club of Vernon</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>New Car Dealers Association of Vernon</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Home Depot</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Rona</strong></p>', 'UNDER RENOVATION', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '769-revision-7', '', '', '2014-06-09 18:41:20', '2014-06-09 18:41:20', '', 769, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2014/06/769-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1030, 2, '2014-06-09 18:41:34', '2014-06-09 18:41:34', '<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>DONATION OF EXERCISE EQUIPMENT BY FLAMAN FITNESS</strong></p>\r\n<a href=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/flaman.jpg\"><img class=\" wp-image-764 aligncenter\" title=\"flaman\" src=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/10/flaman-290x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"193\" height=\"211\" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe <strong>Vernon Women\'s Transition House</strong> is able to offer yet another service to those in need thanks to a donation by <strong>Flaman Fitness</strong>.  Working through the Frank Flaman Foundation, the charity arm of the Flaman Group of Companies, the Vernon fitness franchise recently installed about $30,000 in gym equipment for the non-profit society.  Brooke McLardy, Programs Director with Transition House, commented that the new equipment represents another layer of support for its clients.  The organization already offers room and board for up to 25 women and children fleeing their homes for safety reasons, Counselling Services, Outreach Programs, Legal Advocacy and groups for women. <em> \"It\'s a recreational opportunity for them,\"</em> said McLardy.  <em>\"They can get some fitness and stress relief without having to leave the house, where their safety might be compromised.\"</em>  Among the equipment is a Bowflex tread climber, Tuff Stuff universal gym, as well as a pair of Freemotion treadmills, elipitcal trainer and recumbent bike.  Staff have also set up a separate quiet room that houses a massage chair and other relaxation equipment. <em> \"We\'ve had a lot of women in the house over the last couple of months just going for it on those machines,\"</em> said McLardy, who noted staff are also taking advantage of the new equipment. <em> \"I was a little bit surprised.  I wasn\'t sure how much the clients would use it.  I was happy we were getting it, but curious how it would be, but they\'ve been on it.\" </em> Laughing, she added: \"<em>It\'s right below my office and I hear it all day long.\"</em>  The Vernon franchise, one of more than 30 in Western Canada and Ontario, installed the equipment and followed up with a tutorial session with staff so they could show clients how to use it properly.  <em>\"The staff were fantastic,\"</em> said McLardy.  <em>\"The setup was painless.  Two or three guys brought in all the machines in all the cardboard and Styrofoam and they cleaned up every scrap. </em><em>They were super respectful when they were here and got it done wiht no fuss at all.\" </em> Colby Russell, Vernon Store Manager, was thrilled to support the women\'s shelter, but noted that going into an environment such as the Transition House requires more sensitivity than with a typical client. <em> \"It\'s kind of a touchy situation to go into a shelter, especially when in the fitness world there are pretty outgoing men,\"</em> said Russell, 28. <em> \"It\'s tricky to go in there and not startle anyone.\" </em> Russell, who has been in the fitness industry for seven years, said the really difficult part is giving away free product.  Most organizations he approaches usually think its\' a scam.  Flaman Fitness has only been open in Vernon since November, so it is new to most people. <em> \"Most charities are like \'What do you want from us?\" or \'You\'re tricking us\',\"</em> said Russell.   <em>\"That was the fun part about it, trying to convince them that, yes, it\'s true, and yes, we really want to do this.\" </em> Flaman Fitness, based in Saskatchewan, is the largest fitness equipment supplier in Canada, employing more than 200 people.  The company, founded by Frank Flaman in 1959, originally started as an agricultural operation, and has since diversified into trailers, fitness equipment (including rentals) and even security systems.  The foundation donates $2 million in equipment annually to charities in Canada and around the world.  <em>\"We are highly encouraged to go out in the community and find charities to donate that product to get them going and help them out,\"</em> said Russell. <em> \"With our foundation,  we have guidelines and restrictions on who we can donate to.  Women and children in need are our only candidate.\" </em> Some of the global charities the foundation supports include World Vision, Change for Children, Operation Eye Sight and the Mother Teresa Missionarries of Charity.', 'FLAMAN SHAPES UP TRANSITION HOUSE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '763-revision-5', '', '', '2014-06-09 18:41:34', '2014-06-09 18:41:34', '', 763, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2014/06/763-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1031, 2, '2014-06-09 18:42:27', '2014-06-09 18:42:27', 'By Vernon Morning Star\r\n\r\nPublished: April 21, 2013 01:00 AM\r\n\r\n<strong>Leadership has shifted at the Vernon Women\'s Transition House Society.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Ninke Beeksma</strong> takes over as Executive Director from Debby Hamilton who held the position for 12 years.\r\n\r\n\"I\'m impressed with the variety of excellent programs offered by the society, as well as the wonderful and caring staff,\" said Beeksma.\r\n\r\n\"My objective is to have a positive impact with the organization\'s success through hands-on-leadership, efficient operations and a respectful work environment where employees can thrive.\"\r\n\r\nBeeksma has an education in business and experience in planning, development, implementation and control of financial and human resources management functions in the non-profit sector.\r\n\r\nHamilton is taking up new duties with the Community Coordination for Women\'s Safety, which provides training and supports to communities to enhance responses to violence against women.\r\n\r\nBeeksma is impressed with Hamilton\'s contributions to Transition House.\r\n\r\n\"Debby achieved many successes, including developing stable support for the programs provided to the community,\" said Beeksma.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><a href=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/VWTS2013-008.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone  wp-image-691\" title=\"VWTS2013 008\" src=\"http://localhost/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/VWTS2013-008-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"220\" height=\"182\" /></a></p>', 'NEW DIRECTOR AT TRANSITION HOUSE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '690-revision-6', '', '', '2014-06-09 18:42:27', '2014-06-09 18:42:27', '', 690, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2014/06/690-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1032, 2, '2014-06-09 18:42:41', '2014-06-09 18:42:41', 'A new strategy to reduce domestic violence is garnering support in the North Okanagan.\r\n\r\nThe provincial government says more than 20,000 professionals will receive training on addressing domestic violence.\r\n\r\n“It’s exactly what’s needed if there is follow-through and agencies do work together,” said Debby Hamilton, with the Vernon Women’s Transition House Society.\r\n\r\nThis year, training on recognizing and responding to domestic violence is being provided to 4,000 school personnel and community partners and 2,500 support workers in victim services, violence against women, and transition house programs.\r\n\r\nAlso as part of the plan, 3,500 Ministry of Children and Family Development staff, and an additional 13,000 school personnel, will receive training starting in 2013. Police officers will receive additional training on assessing risk and safety planning.\r\n\r\nStarting this year, there will be an enhanced flagging system in the integrated justice information database for files involving child victims.\r\n\r\nThe strategy will also look at all domestic violence training programs for service providers across government to identify strengths, duplications and gaps.\r\n\r\nHamilton is pleased that specific timelines have been established for reaching these goals.\r\n\r\n“I worry when initiatives become politicized and may bridge an election, but because there are tight timelines, that makes me feel better,” she said.\r\n\r\nHamilton’s only concern is agencies may not have the resources available to proceed with the strategy.\r\n\r\n“It needs to have some dollars attached with it,” she said.\r\n\r\nThe plan was developed in consultation with the ministries of children and family development, health, justice, social development, education and aboriginal relations.\r\n\r\nBy <a href=\"http://www.vernonmorningstar.com/news/173959011.html\">Richard Rolke - Vernon Morning Star\r\n</a>October 14, 2012', 'Domestic violence plan gains local proponents', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '161-revision-9', '', '', '2014-06-09 18:42:41', '2014-06-09 18:42:41', '', 161, 'http://localhost/wordpress/2014/06/161-revision-9/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
